{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585334"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:09:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:09:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14957"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14957"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.05,0.26,0.46,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7645"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7645"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14957"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98349"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6798"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8109"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18703"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents with a five-day history of fever, productive cough, and progressive shortness of breath. Clinical examination and chest X-ray confirm right lower lobe pneumonia with dense consolidation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the predominant histological finding in the affected lung tissue at this stage of lobar pneumonia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alveolar spaces containing lymphocytes","Alveolar spaces containing erythrocytes","Alveolar spaces containing macrophages","Alveolar spaces containing neutrophils","Alveolar spaces containing fibroblasts"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the five-day duration of symptoms, this patient is in the grey hepatisation stage of lobar pneumonia. At this stage, \u003Cstrong\u003Ealveolar spaces containing neutrophils\u003C/strong\u003E is the predominant histological finding, along with fibrinopurulent exudate. The tissue becomes airless and firm, resembling liver tissue, hence the term \u0027hepatisation\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlveolar spaces containing erythrocytes\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the earlier red hepatisation stage (24-48 hours). \u003Cstrong\u003EAlveolar spaces containing lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E is more typical of viral or interstitial pneumonias. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlveolar spaces containing macrophages\u003C/strong\u003E characterises the later resolution phase. \u003Cstrong\u003EAlveolar spaces containing fibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate chronic inflammation or fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these pathological stages helps predict disease progression and guides clinical management. The progression from red to grey hepatisation represents the peak inflammatory response, after which resolution typically begins with appropriate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Grey hepatisation is the second stage of lobar pneumonia, characterised by fibrinopurulent exudate and neutrophil infiltration.","The progression of lobar pneumonia follows four stages: congestion, red hepatisation, grey hepatisation, and resolution.","Understanding the pathological stages of pneumonia helps clinicians anticipate complications and monitor recovery."],"references":["Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Jain V, Vashisht R, Yilmaz G, et al. Pneumonia Pathology. [Updated 2023 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK526116/","Vaughn VM, Dickson RP, Horowitz JK, Flanders SA. Community-Acquired Pneumonia: A Review. JAMA. 2024 Oct 15;332(15):1282-1295. doi: 10.1001/jama.2024.14796. PMID: 39283629"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98349"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14957"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98349"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T17:07:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T17:07:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7645"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116352"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms"